# Week 1 — Project Planning & Lab Design

## Overview

Week 1 focuses on the **planning and architectural design** of the ICS-RedSim SCADA/ICS security lab.
The objective of this phase is to define the **scope, system architecture, network segmentation, and technology stack** required to build a virtual industrial control system environment.

This step ensures that the lab is **safe, isolated, and capable of simulating industrial cyber incidents** without affecting real systems.

---

# Objectives

The goals of Week 1 are:

* Define the project scope and safety guidelines
* Design the ICS lab architecture
* Select appropriate tools and technologies
* Create an IP addressing plan
* Define network zones similar to real ICS environments

---

# Lab Design Principles

Industrial networks typically follow a **segmented architecture** to separate operational technology (OT) from IT infrastructure.

The lab environment was designed to mimic this concept by separating the system into multiple zones.

### Key Design Principles

* Isolation of OT systems
* Segmentation between monitoring and control layers
* Controlled testing environment
* Safe simulation of industrial incidents

---

# ICS Network Architecture

The lab follows a **zone-based architecture**, similar to industrial security models used in real-world SCADA systems.

### Network Zones

| Zone                  | Description                                             |
| --------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| IT Zone               | Analyst workstation for monitoring and analysis         |
| DMZ / Monitoring Zone | Security monitoring tools (IDS and SIEM)                |
| OT Zone               | Industrial devices including PLC and SCADA              |
| Attacker/Test Zone    | Controlled environment for security scenario simulation |

---

# Architecture Diagram

The architecture diagram illustrates the communication flow between the SCADA system, PLC, and monitoring tools.

```
IT Zone
   |
   | Monitoring
   |
DMZ Zone
   |
   | IDS / SIEM Monitoring
   |
OT Zone
   |-------------------|
   |                   |
OpenPLC (PLC)     FUXA (SCADA/HMI)
   |
   |
Industrial Process Simulation
```

This structure allows monitoring tools to observe industrial network traffic without directly interfering with the process control system.

---

# Virtualization Platform

The project uses **VMware Workstation Player** to build the virtual lab environment.

Virtualization allows multiple machines to run in a single host system while maintaining network isolation.

Advantages include:

* Cost-effective ICS lab simulation
* Safe testing environment
* Easy replication and scalability

---

# Technology Stack

The following technologies were selected for the lab implementation.

| Tool               | Purpose                                  |
| ------------------ | ---------------------------------------- |
| VMware Workstation | Virtual lab environment                  |
| OpenPLC            | PLC logic simulation                     |
| FUXA               | SCADA/HMI interface                      |
| Suricata           | Network Intrusion Detection System       |
| Wazuh              | Security monitoring and SIEM             |
| Wireshark          | Network packet analysis                  |
| Kali Linux         | Security testing and incident simulation |

---

# Network IP Addressing Plan

The following IP scheme is used to organize the virtual ICS network.

| Device        | IP Address    | Role                     |
| ------------- | ------------- | ------------------------ |
| PLC VM        | 192.168.x.x | OpenPLC Controller       |
| SCADA VM      | 192.168.x.x | FUXA HMI                 |
| Monitoring VM | 192.168.x.x | Suricata + Wazuh         |
| Attacker VM   | 192.168.x.x | Security testing machine |

Each zone is placed in a separate network segment to simulate realistic industrial network design.

